# Research Complete: AI-Generated Rust Code Flaws, Mistakes, and Anti-Patterns

## Research Summary

Thorough web research has been conducted across 30+ sources including academic papers, blog posts, developer forums, Microsoft Research publications, HuggingFace technical reports, and security analyses. Below are all findings structured by category, ready for conversion to a comprehensive markdown document.

---

# COMPREHENSIVE FINDINGS

---

## 1. OWNERSHIP AND BORROWING MISTAKES

### Flaw: Returning References to Locally-Owned Data

**Description:** AI models frequently generate functions that attempt to return a reference to data owned by the function, which violates Rust's ownership rules. The reference would dangle after the function returns.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn get_first_word(s: String) -> &str {
    for (i, &item) in s.as_bytes().iter().enumerate() {
        if item == b' ' {
            return &s[0..i]; // ERROR: returning reference to local data
        }
    }
    &s[..]
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn get_first_word(s: &str) -> &str {
    for (i, &item) in s.as_bytes().iter().enumerate() {
        if item == b' ' {
            return &s[0..i];
        }
    }
    s
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Models trained primarily on garbage-collected languages (Python, JavaScript, Java) don't internalize that references cannot outlive the data they point to. In GC languages, returning a reference to local data is perfectly safe.

**Impact:** Compilation failure (E0106). Not a runtime risk since the compiler catches it, but it wastes developer time in iteration cycles.

**Detection:** `cargo check` catches this immediately. The compiler error E0106 ("missing lifetime specifier") is clear.

**Statistics:** Ownership and borrowing violations account for **over 40% of compilation errors** in AI-generated Rust code (Source: Strand-Rust-Coder tech report).

**Sources:**
- https://dev.to/tigranbs/coding-rust-with-claude-code-and-codex-2c4j
- https://huggingface.co/blog/Fortytwo-Network/strand-rust-coder-tech-report

---

### Flaw: Simultaneous Mutable and Immutable Borrows

**Description:** AI generates code that borrows a value mutably and immutably at the same time, violating Rust's aliasing rules.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn process(data: &mut Vec<i32>) {
    let first = &data[0];      // immutable borrow
    data.push(42);              // mutable borrow -- ERROR
    println!("{}", first);      // use of immutable borrow
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn process(data: &mut Vec<i32>) {
    let first = data[0];       // copy the value instead of borrowing
    data.push(42);
    println!("{}", first);
}
// OR restructure to separate the borrows temporally
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** LLMs generate code line-by-line in sequence and don't track the "borrow state" across the function body. The pattern of "read then modify" is extremely common in other languages.

**Impact:** Compilation failure (E0502). Requires architectural restructuring, not just syntax fixes.

**Detection:** `cargo check` with error E0502 ("cannot borrow `x` as mutable because it is also borrowed as immutable").

**Sources:**
- https://dev.to/tigranbs/coding-rust-with-claude-code-and-codex-2c4j
- https://rust-book.cs.brown.edu/ch04-03-fixing-ownership-errors.html

---

### Flaw: Missing `move` Keyword in Thread Closures

**Description:** AI generates closures for thread spawning that capture variables by reference instead of by value, violating `'static` lifetime bounds.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
let data = vec![1, 2, 3];
let handle = std::thread::spawn(|| {
    println!("{:?}", data);  // ERROR: closure may outlive current function
});
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
let data = vec![1, 2, 3];
let handle = std::thread::spawn(move || {
    println!("{:?}", data);  // data is moved into the closure
});
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** In most other languages, closures automatically capture by reference and the GC handles lifetime. AI models default to this familiar pattern.

**Impact:** Compilation failure. The compiler provides helpful error messages suggesting `move`.

**Sources:**
- https://dev.to/tigranbs/coding-rust-with-claude-code-and-codex-2c4j

---

## 2. LIFETIME ANNOTATION ERRORS

### Flaw: Incorrect or Unnecessary Lifetime Annotations

**Description:** AI models either omit required lifetime annotations or add unnecessary/incorrect ones. A common pattern is applying the same lifetime to all references when they should have different lifetimes.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
// AI gives everything the same lifetime
fn longest<'a>(x: &'a str, y: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    x  // Only depends on x's lifetime, not y's
}

// Or worse: elided lifetimes that are silently wrong
struct Parser {
    input: &str,  // ERROR: missing lifetime annotation
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn first<'a>(x: &'a str, _y: &str) -> &'a str {
    x  // Lifetime correctly tied only to x
}

struct Parser<'a> {
    input: &'a str,
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Lifetime elision rules are subtle, and the compiler's suggestions for fixing lifetime errors will make the program compile but may not reflect the actual intended data flow. AI models follow the "make it compile" approach.

**Impact:** May compile but can over-constrain or under-constrain the API, leading to usability issues or forcing callers to hold borrows longer than necessary.

**Key Insight:** "The compiler's error messages suggest fixes which will make your program compile, but this is not the same as fixes which will make your program compile and best suit the requirements of your program."

**Detection:** `cargo clippy` can catch some unnecessary lifetime annotations. Code review is essential for semantic correctness.

**Sources:**
- https://github.com/pretzelhammer/rust-blog/blob/master/posts/common-rust-lifetime-misconceptions.md
- https://corrode.dev/blog/lifetimes/
- https://users.rust-lang.org/t/blog-post-common-rust-lifetime-misconceptions/42950

---

### Flaw: Overusing Borrowed References When Owned Types Suffice

**Description:** AI models sometimes create structs with borrowed references that should own their data, leading to lifetime annotation proliferation.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
struct Config<'a> {
    name: &'a str,
    path: &'a str,
    values: &'a [i32],
}
// Now every function using Config needs lifetime annotations
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
struct Config {
    name: String,
    path: String,
    values: Vec<i32>,
}
// Clean, owned data -- no lifetime propagation
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Models see both patterns in training data and may prefer the "more Rust-looking" version with references and lifetimes, not understanding that owned types are often simpler and more appropriate.

**Impact:** Lifetime annotation proliferation makes code harder to read, maintain, and extend. Can create unnecessary coupling between data structures.

**Sources:**
- https://corrode.dev/blog/lifetimes/
- https://dev.to/sgchris/avoiding-lifetime-annotations-with-structs-16ni

---

## 3. UNSAFE CODE MISUSE

### Flaw: Unnecessary or Incorrect Use of `unsafe` Blocks

**Description:** AI models may insert `unsafe` blocks to work around borrow checker errors rather than finding safe solutions, or generate unsafe code with incorrect invariants (e.g., invalid pointer arithmetic, incorrect `transmute` usage).

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn get_value(data: &[i32], index: usize) -> i32 {
    unsafe {
        *data.as_ptr().add(index)  // Unnecessary -- no bounds check
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn get_value(data: &[i32], index: usize) -> Option<i32> {
    data.get(index).copied()
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** AI models may see `unsafe` as a "bypass" for compiler restrictions. Training data includes unsafe code from FFI bindings and performance-critical code, which models may apply inappropriately.

**Impact:** Critical. Introduces memory safety vulnerabilities including buffer overflows, use-after-free, double-free, and arbitrary memory access. Research shows these are the exact vulnerability types found in unsafe Rust (deepSURF found 26 memory safety bugs including 6 previously unknown ones).

**Detection:** `cargo-geiger` scans for unsafe usage. `cargo clippy` flags some unnecessary unsafe blocks. Code review is essential.

**Statistics:** 20% of Rust crates use the `unsafe` keyword; AI may over-represent this pattern.

**Sources:**
- https://arxiv.org/html/2506.15648v1 (deepSURF)
- https://arxiv.org/html/2503.10793v1 (HALURust)
- https://developers.slashdot.org/story/24/05/25/2250236/rust-foundation-reports-20-of-rust-crates-use-unsafe-keyword

---

## 4. ERROR HANDLING (UNWRAP ABUSE, POOR RESULT/OPTION HANDLING)

### Flaw: Pervasive Use of `.unwrap()` and `.expect()`

**Description:** AI models overwhelmingly use `.unwrap()` on `Result` and `Option` types instead of proper error handling. This is arguably the single most common AI Rust anti-pattern.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn read_config(path: &str) -> Config {
    let content = std::fs::read_to_string(path).unwrap();
    let config: Config = serde_json::from_str(&content).unwrap();
    config
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn read_config(path: &str) -> Result<Config, Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let content = std::fs::read_to_string(path)?;
    let config: Config = serde_json::from_str(&content)?;
    Ok(config)
}

// Or with specific error types using thiserror:
#[derive(thiserror::Error, Debug)]
enum ConfigError {
    #[error("Failed to read config file: {0}")]
    Io(#[from] std::io::Error),
    #[error("Failed to parse config: {0}")]
    Parse(#[from] serde_json::Error),
}

fn read_config(path: &str) -> Result<Config, ConfigError> {
    let content = std::fs::read_to_string(path)?;
    let config: Config = serde_json::from_str(&content)?;
    Ok(config)
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Training examples, tutorials, and documentation snippets heavily use `.unwrap()` for brevity. AI models don't distinguish between example code and production code. The `.unwrap()` pattern is the shortest path to making code compile.

**Impact:** Runtime panics in production. Panics terminate the thread (or program), skip cleanup, and can leak resources. Error details are lost, making debugging difficult.

**Detection:** `cargo clippy` with `-W clippy::unwrap_used` flag. Search codebase for `.unwrap()` calls outside of test modules.

**Sources:**
- https://medium.com/@InTheRiot/mastering-rust-error-handling-ditch-unwrap-and-write-safer-cleaner-code-368791314949
- https://www.thecodedmessage.com/posts/2022-07-14-programming-unwrap/
- https://burntsushi.net/unwrap/

---

## 5. TRAIT IMPLEMENTATION ISSUES

### Flaw: Object Safety Violations with `dyn Trait`

**Description:** AI models generate trait definitions that are not object-safe, then attempt to use them as trait objects (`dyn Trait`), causing compilation errors.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
trait Processor {
    fn process(&self) -> Self;  // Returns Self -- not object-safe
    fn clone_box(&self) -> Box<dyn Processor>;  // Can't use dyn with non-object-safe trait
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
trait Processor {
    fn process(&self) -> Box<dyn Processor>;  // Returns trait object instead
    fn clone_box(&self) -> Box<dyn Processor>;
}

// Or use associated types / generics instead of dyn
trait Processor: Sized {
    fn process(&self) -> Self;
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Object safety rules are nuanced (no `Self` in return types, no generic methods, etc.). Models from OOP languages generate trait hierarchies that assume runtime polymorphism works like class inheritance.

**Impact:** Compilation failure (E0038). Requires rethinking the trait design.

**Sources:**
- https://doc.rust-lang.org/error_codes/E0038.html
- https://quinedot.github.io/rust-learning/dyn-safety.html

---

### Flaw: Using `format!()` Instead of `write!()` in Display Implementations

**Description:** When implementing `Display` trait, AI uses `format!()` which creates an unnecessary temporary `String` allocation.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
impl fmt::Display for Point {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        // Creates temporary String, then writes it
        write!(f, "{}", format!("({}, {})", self.x, self.y))
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
impl fmt::Display for Point {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "({}, {})", self.x, self.y)  // Writes directly, no allocation
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** `format!()` is more commonly seen in training data and appears "safer" or more readable. The distinction between writing to a formatter vs. creating a string is subtle.

**Impact:** Performance: unnecessary heap allocation on every display call. Particularly bad in logging-heavy applications.

**Sources:**
- https://huggingface.co/blog/Fortytwo-Network/strand-rust-coder-tech-report

---

## 6. CONCURRENCY PROBLEMS

### Flaw: Holding Locks Across Await Points

**Description:** AI generates async code that holds `MutexGuard` across `.await` points, leading to deadlocks or thread starvation.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
async fn update_cache(cache: Arc<Mutex<HashMap<String, String>>>) {
    let mut guard = cache.lock().unwrap();
    let value = fetch_from_db().await;  // Lock held across await!
    guard.insert("key".to_string(), value);
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
async fn update_cache(cache: Arc<Mutex<HashMap<String, String>>>) {
    let value = fetch_from_db().await;  // Fetch first
    let mut guard = cache.lock().unwrap();
    guard.insert("key".to_string(), value);  // Then lock and insert
}
// Or use explicit scoping:
async fn update_cache(cache: Arc<Mutex<HashMap<String, String>>>) {
    let value = fetch_from_db().await;
    {
        let mut guard = cache.lock().unwrap();
        guard.insert("key".to_string(), value);
    }  // Guard dropped here
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The sequential "lock -> use -> unlock" pattern is natural in synchronous code. AI doesn't understand that await points yield control, and the lock would block the entire async runtime.

**Impact:** Deadlocks, thread starvation, severe performance degradation in async applications.

**Detection:** `cargo clippy` has `await_holding_lock` lint. Tokio's `tracing` can help identify lock contention at runtime.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async
- https://effective-rust.com/deadlock.html

---

### Flaw: Lock Ordering Inversions

**Description:** AI generates code that acquires multiple locks in different orders across different functions, causing deadlocks.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn transfer(from: &Mutex<Account>, to: &Mutex<Account>, amount: f64) {
    let mut from_guard = from.lock().unwrap();
    let mut to_guard = to.lock().unwrap();  // Deadlock if another thread locks in reverse order
    from_guard.balance -= amount;
    to_guard.balance += amount;
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn transfer(from: &Mutex<Account>, to: &Mutex<Account>, amount: f64) {
    // Always acquire locks in consistent order (e.g., by address)
    let (mut first, mut second) = if std::ptr::from_ref(from) < std::ptr::from_ref(to) {
        (from.lock().unwrap(), to.lock().unwrap())
    } else {
        (to.lock().unwrap(), from.lock().unwrap())
    };
    // ... perform transfer
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Lock ordering is an architectural concern that requires whole-program reasoning. AI generates code locally and cannot track lock acquisition patterns across different functions.

**Impact:** Deadlocks in production that may be rare and hard to reproduce.

**Detection:** `parking_lot::deadlock` detection, ThreadSanitizer, `no_deadlocks` crate.

**Sources:**
- https://effective-rust.com/deadlock.html
- https://www.snoyman.com/blog/2024/01/best-worst-deadlock-rust/

---

### Flaw: Using Async Mutex When Sync Mutex Suffices

**Description:** AI defaults to `tokio::sync::Mutex` in all async contexts, even when `std::sync::Mutex` would be more efficient.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
let workers = Arc::new(tokio::sync::Mutex::new(HashMap::new()));
for i in 1..10 {
    let workers = workers.clone();
    tokio::spawn(async move {
        let mut workers = workers.lock().await;  // Unnecessary async overhead
        workers.insert(i, i);
    });
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
let workers = Arc::new(std::sync::Mutex::new(HashMap::new()));
for i in 1..10 {
    let workers = workers.clone();
    tokio::spawn(async move {
        let mut workers = workers.lock().unwrap();  // Sync mutex is fine here
        workers.insert(i, i);
    });
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** "If we're in async code, everything should be async" is a common misconception. AI applies this rule uniformly.

**Impact:** Performance overhead from unnecessary async machinery when the lock is held briefly and never across await points.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

---

## 7. PERFORMANCE ANTI-PATTERNS

### Flaw: Over-Reliance on `.clone()` to Satisfy the Borrow Checker

**Description:** The single most common performance anti-pattern in AI-generated Rust code. Instead of restructuring code to work with Rust's ownership model, AI sprinkles `.clone()` everywhere to make the compiler happy.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn process_items(items: &Vec<String>) {
    for item in items.clone() {         // Clones entire Vec
        let upper = item.clone().to_uppercase();  // Clones each String
        println!("{}", upper);
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn process_items(items: &[String]) {    // Accept slice, not &Vec
    for item in items {
        let upper = item.to_uppercase();  // No clone needed
        println!("{}", upper);
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** `.clone()` is the fastest way to resolve borrow checker errors. AI optimizes for "compiles successfully" rather than "performs well." This is directly analogous to how a beginner Rust developer solves borrow checker issues.

**Impact:** Severe performance degradation. Naive Rust clones are **3-5x slower** than equivalent operations in GC languages because Rust performs deep copies. Cloning a `Vec<String>` with thousands of elements means thousands of heap allocations. A 10K element vector: 622ns standard clone vs 41ns with Arc = 15x speedup.

**Detection:** `cargo clippy` catches some unnecessary clones. Profile with `flamegraph` or `cargo bench`.

**Sources:**
- https://rust-unofficial.github.io/patterns/anti_patterns/borrow_clone.html
- https://hamy.xyz/blog/2026-02_the-problem-with-clones-in-rust

---

### Flaw: Using `String` Parameters Instead of `&str`

**Description:** AI generates function signatures that take `String` (owned) when `&str` (borrowed) would suffice, forcing callers to allocate or clone.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn greet(name: String) {
    println!("Hello, {}!", name);
}

// Caller must allocate:
greet("World".to_string());  // Unnecessary heap allocation
greet(my_string.clone());    // Unnecessary clone
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn greet(name: &str) {
    println!("Hello, {}!", name);
}

// Caller can pass either:
greet("World");           // No allocation
greet(&my_string);        // No clone
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** `String` appears more in training data than `&str` for function parameters. Using owned types "just works" without thinking about borrowing.

**Impact:** Unnecessary heap allocations on every call. Particularly impactful in hot paths.

**Detection:** `cargo clippy` warns about `&String` parameters (should be `&str`). Review function signatures.

**Sources:**
- https://dev.to/sgchris/why-str-is-better-than-string-in-parameters-4jn0
- https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy/issues/7933

---

### Flaw: Using `&Vec<T>` Instead of `&[T]` in Function Parameters

**Description:** Similar to the String issue: AI uses `&Vec<T>` when `&[T]` (slice) is more general and idiomatic.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn sum(numbers: &Vec<i32>) -> i32 {
    numbers.iter().sum()
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn sum(numbers: &[i32]) -> i32 {
    numbers.iter().sum()
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Same reason as String vs &str -- owned types are more common in training data.

**Impact:** Forces callers to have a Vec specifically, when arrays, slices, or other contiguous memory would also work.

**Detection:** `cargo clippy` lint `clippy::ptr_arg`.

**Sources:**
- https://llogiq.github.io/2017/06/01/perf-pitfalls.html

---

### Flaw: Unnecessary Allocations in Loops

**Description:** AI creates new allocations inside loops instead of reusing buffers.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn process_lines(input: &str) {
    for line in input.lines() {
        let processed = String::new();  // New allocation each iteration
        // ... process into `processed`
        println!("{}", processed);
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn process_lines(input: &str) {
    let mut processed = String::new();  // Reuse allocation
    for line in input.lines() {
        processed.clear();  // Reset without deallocating
        // ... process into `processed`
        println!("{}", processed);
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Creating fresh variables in each iteration is the "clean" pattern in GC languages. AI doesn't consider allocation costs.

**Impact:** O(n) heap allocations where O(1) would suffice. Significant in high-throughput code.

**Sources:**
- https://nnethercote.github.io/perf-book/heap-allocations.html

---

### Flaw: Not Using Iterators / Collecting Prematurely

**Description:** AI collects iterator results into a Vec when the iterator could be consumed lazily, or chains multiple collect() calls unnecessarily.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
let evens: Vec<i32> = numbers.iter()
    .filter(|&&x| x % 2 == 0)
    .cloned()
    .collect();  // Allocates intermediate Vec
let doubled: Vec<i32> = evens.iter()
    .map(|&x| x * 2)
    .collect();  // Another allocation
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
let doubled: Vec<i32> = numbers.iter()
    .filter(|&&x| x % 2 == 0)
    .map(|&x| x * 2)
    .collect();  // Single allocation
// Or if only iterating, don't collect at all:
for value in numbers.iter().filter(|&&x| x % 2 == 0).map(|&x| x * 2) {
    // process value
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Step-by-step thinking leads to step-by-step code. AI generates one transformation at a time instead of chaining.

**Impact:** Multiple unnecessary heap allocations and data copies.

**Sources:**
- https://llogiq.github.io/2017/06/01/perf-pitfalls.html

---

## 8. MACRO MISUSE

### Flaw: Incorrect Procedural Macro Syntax and Structure

**Description:** AI generates procedural macros with incorrect crate naming (`proc-macro` vs `proc_macro`), missing dependencies, or code that doesn't follow proc macro conventions.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
// AI suggests in Cargo.toml:
[dependencies]
proc-macro = "1.0"  // WRONG: proc_macro is built-in, not a crate

// AI generates macro with incorrect token handling
#[proc_macro_derive(MyDerive)]
pub fn my_derive(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    // Uses format!() to construct output instead of quote!
    let output = format!("impl MyTrait for {} {{}}", struct_name);
    output.parse().unwrap()  // Fragile string parsing
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
// Cargo.toml:
[lib]
proc-macro = true

[dependencies]
syn = "2"
quote = "1"
proc-macro2 = "1"

// Proper macro using syn and quote:
#[proc_macro_derive(MyDerive)]
pub fn my_derive(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    let input = parse_macro_input!(input as DeriveInput);
    let name = &input.ident;
    let expanded = quote! {
        impl MyTrait for #name {}
    };
    TokenStream::from(expanded)
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Proc macros have a unique project structure. AI conflates the `proc_macro` built-in crate with external dependencies. String-based code generation is simpler to produce than proper AST manipulation.

**Impact:** Compilation failures. Fragile macros that break on edge cases.

**Sources:**
- https://dev.to/sidunn/macro-roni-ai-yi-yi-3fce

---

## 9. CARGO/DEPENDENCY ISSUES (HALLUCINATED CRATES)

### Flaw: Recommending Non-Existent Crates

**Description:** AI models confidently suggest Rust crates that do not exist on crates.io, a problem known as "package hallucination" or "slopsquatting."

**Example:**
```toml
# AI-generated Cargo.toml with hallucinated dependencies
[dependencies]
rust-web-framework = "0.5"     # Does not exist
easy-async-runtime = "1.2"      # Does not exist
simple-database-orm = "0.3"     # Does not exist
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** LLMs generate package names based on statistical patterns, not by verifying against live registries. They cannot query crates.io during generation. Research shows **19.7% of all package dependencies** (440,445 out of 576,000 samples across 16 LLMs) were hallucinated. Open-source models hallucinate at ~21.7% vs commercial models at ~5.2%.

**Impact:** Critical security risk. Attackers register hallucinated package names ("slopsquatting") and plant malicious code. 43% of hallucinations repeat across queries, making them predictable attack targets.

**Detection:** Verify all crate names on crates.io before adding to Cargo.toml. Use `cargo audit` for known vulnerabilities.

**Sources:**
- https://www.usenix.org/publications/loginonline/we-have-package-you-comprehensive-analysis-package-hallucinations-code
- https://arxiv.org/html/2501.19012v1
- https://snyk.io/articles/package-hallucinations/
- https://cacm.acm.org/news/nonsense-and-malicious-packages-llm-hallucinations-in-code-generation/
- https://www.darkreading.com/application-security/ai-code-tools-widely-hallucinate-packages

---

### Flaw: Outdated or Incorrect Crate Versions and APIs

**Description:** AI suggests crate versions that are outdated, or uses APIs that have been removed or renamed in newer versions.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
// Using deprecated API from an old version of reqwest
let body = reqwest::get("https://example.com").unwrap().text().unwrap();

// Should be async in modern reqwest:
let body = reqwest::get("https://example.com").await?.text().await?;
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Training data includes code from many time periods. AI doesn't know which version of a crate is current.

**Impact:** Build failures, deprecated APIs, missing security patches.

**Sources:**
- https://www.ksred.com/ai-coding-effectiveness-in-2025-avoiding-critical-mistakes-and-security-risks-in-production/

---

## 10. CODE THAT COMPILES BUT IS SEMANTICALLY WRONG

### Flaw: Plausible but Incorrect Business Logic

**Description:** AI generates code that compiles, passes basic tests, and looks architecturally sound but contains deep semantic errors that only surface under real workloads.

**Real-World Example:** An LLM-generated Rust reimplementation of SQLite (576,000 lines, 625 files) had a query planner that only checked for literal strings "rowid", "_rowid_", and "oid" -- missing that `INTEGER PRIMARY KEY` columns are aliases for the internal rowid. This caused every `WHERE id = N` query to perform a full table scan (O(n)) instead of a B-tree lookup (O(log n)), resulting in a **20,171x slowdown**.

**Another Example:** Every INSERT outside a transaction triggered a full `fsync()` call. 100 inserts = 100 disk syncs, causing **1,857x slowdown** vs batched mode.

**Why AI makes this mistake:** "LLMs optimize for plausibility, not correctness." They generate code that looks right based on surface-level patterns but miss domain-specific invariants and optimization rules. Semantic errors make up **over 60% of faults** in AI-generated code.

**Impact:** Catastrophic performance degradation, data corruption, incorrect results that may not be caught by basic tests.

**Detection:** Benchmark against reference implementations. Property-based testing (proptest). Fuzzing. Integration tests with realistic workloads.

**Sources:**
- https://cybercorsairs.com/when-llm-code-looks-right-but-runs-20000x-wrong/
- https://sesamedisk.com/troubleshooting-llm-generated-code/
- https://www.ranger.net/post/common-bugs-ai-generated-code-fixes

---

### Flaw: Off-by-One Errors and Boundary Conditions

**Description:** AI-generated code frequently has off-by-one errors, fails to handle empty inputs, or miscalculates boundary conditions.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
fn find_max(slice: &[i32]) -> i32 {
    let mut max = slice[0];  // Panics on empty slice
    for i in 1..slice.len() - 1 {  // Off-by-one: misses last element
        if slice[i] > max {
            max = slice[i];
        }
    }
    max
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
fn find_max(slice: &[i32]) -> Option<i32> {
    slice.iter().copied().max()  // Handles empty slice, uses all elements
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Boundary conditions require precise reasoning about ranges and edge cases, which statistical models handle poorly.

**Impact:** Runtime panics (empty input), incorrect results (off-by-one).

**Sources:**
- https://www.ranger.net/post/common-bugs-ai-generated-code-fixes

---

## 11. ASYNC RUST MISTAKES

### Flaw: Forgetting About Task Cancellation

**Description:** AI generates async code that assumes tasks always run to completion, putting cleanup logic after await points where it may never execute if the task is cancelled.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
async fn my_task(counter: Arc<AtomicUsize>) {
    counter.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
    do_work().await;
    counter.fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Relaxed);  // May never run if task cancelled
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
async fn my_task(counter: Arc<AtomicUsize>) {
    counter.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
    let _guard = scopeguard::guard((), |_| {
        counter.fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
    });
    do_work().await;
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Task cancellation is an implicit contract in async Rust that has no direct analog in most other languages. AI generates code with implicit "happy path" assumptions.

**Impact:** Resource leaks, incorrect state, counter drift.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

---

### Flaw: `select!` in Loops Creating and Destroying Futures

**Description:** Using `select!` in a loop recreates futures on every iteration, potentially losing buffered data.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
loop {
    tokio::select! {
        _ = abort_signal.recv() => return,
        msg = connection.recv() => {  // Future recreated each iteration
            process(msg).await;
        }
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
let abort = abort_signal.recv().fuse();
pin_mut!(abort);

loop {
    tokio::select! {
        _ = &mut abort => return,
        msg = connection.recv() => {
            process(msg).await;
        }
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The "simple" select-in-loop pattern looks correct and often works for simple cases. The subtle issue of future recreation and data loss requires deep async expertise.

**Impact:** Lost messages, data corruption, non-deterministic behavior under load.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

---

### Flaw: Future Progress Starvation

**Description:** AI generates async code where one future blocks others from making progress.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
async fn serve(listener: TcpListener) {
    loop {
        let (stream, _) = listener.accept().await.unwrap();
        handle_connection(stream).await;  // Blocks accepting new connections
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
async fn serve(listener: TcpListener) {
    loop {
        let (stream, _) = listener.accept().await.unwrap();
        tokio::spawn(async move {
            handle_connection(stream).await;
        });
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Sequential processing looks "correct" and simpler. AI doesn't reason about concurrent throughput.

**Impact:** Server handles only one connection at a time. Dropped connections, missed heartbeats under load.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

---

### Flaw: Holding RAII Guards Across Await Points

**Description:** AI holds resource pool connections or other RAII objects across await points, starving the resource pool.

**Bad Code:**
```rust
async fn fetch_and_process(pool: &Pool) {
    let mut conn = pool.get().await.unwrap();
    let data = sqlx::query("SELECT * FROM items")
        .fetch_all(&mut conn).await.unwrap();
    for item in data {
        expensive_processing(item).await;  // Connection held entire time
    }
}
```

**Good Code:**
```rust
async fn fetch_and_process(pool: &Pool) {
    let data = {
        let mut conn = pool.get().await.unwrap();
        sqlx::query("SELECT * FROM items")
            .fetch_all(&mut conn).await.unwrap()
    };  // Connection returned to pool here
    for item in data {
        expensive_processing(item).await;
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The "fetch then process" pattern naturally keeps the connection alive. Explicit scoping for early resource release requires understanding resource pool semantics.

**Impact:** Pool exhaustion, connection timeouts, cascading failures.

**Sources:**
- https://www.qovery.com/blog/common-mistakes-with-rust-async

