# AI-Generated TypeScript Code: Common Flaws, Mistakes, and Anti-Patterns

## Comprehensive Research Findings

---

## 1. TYPE SAFETY ISSUES

### 1.1 Abuse of `any` Type

**Description:** When AI models cannot determine the correct type, they default to `any`, effectively disabling TypeScript's type system. This has been called "AI catnip" -- agents reach for `any` whenever they encounter type complexity.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
function processUser(data: any) {
  const email = data.user.email;
  return email.toLowerCase();
}

function handleResponse(response: any) {
  return response.data.items.map((item: any) => item.name);
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
interface UserData {
  user: {
    email: string;
  };
}

function processUser(data: UserData): string {
  return data.user.email.toLowerCase();
}

interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: {
    items: T[];
  };
}

function handleResponse(response: ApiResponse<{ name: string }>): string[] {
  return response.data.items.map((item) => item.name);
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Models optimize for code that compiles and runs. Using `any` is the fastest path to eliminating type errors without understanding the domain.

**Impact:** Runtime crashes from accessing properties on undefined/null, loss of IDE autocomplete, defeats the purpose of TypeScript entirely. Errors surface in production instead of at compile time.

**Detection:** ESLint rule `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any`. TypeScript `strict: true` in tsconfig.json.

**Sources:**
- [Lint Against the Machine: AI Coding Agent Anti-Patterns](https://medium.com/@montes.makes/lint-against-the-machine-a-field-guide-to-catching-ai-coding-agent-anti-patterns-3c4ef7baeb9e)
- [5 Things AI Can't Do in TypeScript](https://dev.to/devunionx/5-things-ai-cant-do-even-in-typescript-1ahm)

---

### 1.2 Unsafe Type Assertions (`as` / `as unknown as`)

**Description:** AI uses type assertions to silence the compiler rather than fixing the underlying type mismatch. The double assertion pattern (`as unknown as X`) is particularly dangerous.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
const user = {} as User; // Missing all required fields
console.log(user.profile.bio); // Runtime crash

const config = response.data as unknown as AppConfig; // Double assertion bypasses all checks
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

const userSchema = z.object({
  id: z.number(),
  email: z.string(),
  profile: z.object({ bio: z.string() }).optional(),
});

const user = userSchema.parse(response.data);
console.log(user.profile?.bio);
```

**Why AI does this:** Assertions make code "compile" immediately. AI models optimize for functional output and don't understand that `as` doesn't perform runtime validation.

**Impact:** Type assertions are a lie to the compiler. Missing required properties won't be flagged, leading to runtime crashes that TypeScript was designed to prevent.

**Detection:** ESLint rule `@typescript-eslint/consistent-type-assertions` with `assertionStyle: 'never'` or strict configurations. Use runtime validation libraries (Zod, io-ts) for external data.

**Sources:**
- [Safe TypeScript Type Casting](https://medium.com/@AlexanderObregon/safe-typescript-type-casting-without-surprises-a1afe26a36a1)
- [Understanding "as unknown as" in TypeScript](https://www.omarileon.me/blog/as-unknown-as-typescript)

---

### 1.3 Overcomplicated or Incorrect Generics

**Description:** AI either oversimplifies generics (defaulting to `any`/`unknown`) or overcomplicates them with deeply nested conditional types that are unreadable and sometimes incorrect.

**Bad code (overcomplicated):**
```typescript
// AI-generated type spaghetti
type MappedParameterTypes<P> = P extends { type: "enum"; enum: infer E }
  ? E extends readonly string[]
    ? E[number]
    : string // Falls back to string, losing precision
  : P extends { type: "object[]"; attributes?: never }
    ? any[] // Falls back to any[]
    : P extends { type: "object[]"; attributes: infer A }
      ? MappedParameterTypes<A>[]
      : never;
```

**Bad code (oversimplified):**
```typescript
function merge<T>(a: T, b: T): T {
  return { ...a, ...b }; // Doesn't actually guarantee T shape
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function merge<T extends Record<string, unknown>>(a: T, b: Partial<T>): T {
  return { ...a, ...b };
}
```

**Why AI does this:** AI repeats patterns from training data without understanding type resolution logic. Deep generic chains are pattern-matched, not reasoned about. Nearly 40% of developers reported confusion when debugging overly generic AI implementations.

**Impact:** Overcomplicated types slow the TypeScript compiler, confuse maintainers, and may silently fall through to `any`. Incorrect constraints lose type safety or reject valid inputs.

**Detection:** Code review for generic depth > 3 levels. Cognitive complexity analysis. TypeScript `--noUncheckedIndexedAccess` flag.

**Sources:**
- [Trying to Understand Copilot's Type Spaghetti](https://rtpg.co/2024/03/07/parsing-copilots-type-spaghetti/)
- [5 Things AI Can't Do in TypeScript](https://dev.to/devunionx/5-things-ai-cant-do-even-in-typescript-1ahm)

---

### 1.4 Missing Strict TypeScript Configuration

**Description:** AI-generated projects often use loose tsconfig settings, or AI code assumes non-strict mode behavior.

**Bad tsconfig.json:**
```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": false,
    "noImplicitAny": false,
    "strictNullChecks": false
  }
}
```

**Good tsconfig.json:**
```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,
    "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true,
    "noImplicitReturns": true,
    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true,
    "forceConsistentCasingInFileNames": true
  }
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data includes both strict and non-strict projects. AI chooses whatever compiles first.

**Impact:** Without strict mode, TypeScript misses null/undefined errors, implicit any, and other class of bugs that strict mode catches.

**Detection:** Check tsconfig.json for `"strict": true`. Use `@typescript-eslint/strict-type-checked` config.

---

### 1.5 Hallucinated Properties and Interfaces

**Description:** AI generates properties on interfaces that don't exist in the actual API or data model, or invents interface shapes that don't match real library types.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

const user: User = {
  name: 'John',
  email: 'john@example.com',
  phoneNumber: '555-1234', // Property doesn't exist on User
};
```

**Why AI does this:** Models predict plausible property names based on context patterns. "Most production outages from AI-generated code trace back to data model mismatches that passed code review."

**Impact:** TypeScript catches some of these at compile time (excess property checks), but type assertions bypass this protection. Runtime crashes when accessing non-existent properties.

**Detection:** TypeScript strict mode, runtime validation with Zod/io-ts, integration tests against real APIs.

**Sources:**
- [Debugging AI-Generated Code: 8 Failure Patterns](https://www.augmentcode.com/guides/debugging-ai-generated-code-8-failure-patterns-and-fixes)
- [Common Bugs in AI-Generated Code](https://www.ranger.net/post/common-bugs-ai-generated-code-fixes)

