## 2. RUNTIME ERRORS FROM INCORRECT ASSUMPTIONS

### 2.1 Missing Null/Undefined Checks

**Description:** AI assumes happy-path data shapes and fails to handle null, undefined, or missing nested properties.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
function processUser(data: any) {
  const email = data.user.email; // Crashes if data.user is null/undefined
  return email.toLowerCase(); // Crashes if email is null/undefined
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function processUser(data: unknown): string | null {
  if (
    typeof data === 'object' && data !== null &&
    'user' in data && typeof (data as any).user === 'object' &&
    (data as any).user !== null &&
    'email' in (data as any).user &&
    typeof (data as any).user.email === 'string'
  ) {
    return (data as { user: { email: string } }).user.email.toLowerCase();
  }
  return null;
}

// Or more practically with optional chaining:
function processUser(data: { user?: { email?: string } }): string | null {
  return data?.user?.email?.toLowerCase() ?? null;
}
```

**Why AI does this:** AI models focus on making functional code that works with expected inputs. Training data contains many examples of "happy path" code.

**Impact:** Runtime TypeError crashes. "Silent logic failures make up 60% of faults" in AI-generated code.

**Detection:** TypeScript `strictNullChecks: true`. ESLint rule `@typescript-eslint/no-non-null-assertion`.

**Sources:**
- [Common Bugs in AI-Generated Code](https://www.ranger.net/post/common-bugs-ai-generated-code-fixes)
- [Debugging AI-Generated Code](https://www.augmentcode.com/guides/debugging-ai-generated-code-8-failure-patterns-and-fixes)

---

### 2.2 Off-by-One Errors and Boundary Conditions

**Description:** AI frequently produces off-by-one errors in loops and fails to handle edge cases like empty arrays, zero-length strings, or boundary values.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
function findIndex(arr: number[], target: number): number {
  for (let i = 0; i <= arr.length; i++) { // Off-by-one: should be <
    if (arr[i] === target) return i;
  }
  return -1;
}

function getFirst<T>(arr: T[]): T {
  return arr[0]; // No bounds check; returns undefined for empty array
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function findIndex(arr: number[], target: number): number {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (arr[i] === target) return i;
  }
  return -1;
}

function getFirst<T>(arr: T[]): T | undefined {
  return arr.length > 0 ? arr[0] : undefined;
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Boundary conditions are edge cases that appear infrequently in training data. AI prioritizes the common case.

**Impact:** Array index out of bounds, accessing undefined values, infinite loops.

**Detection:** Unit tests with empty arrays, null values, zero, negative numbers, maximum integers. TypeScript `noUncheckedIndexedAccess: true`.

---

### 2.3 Data Model Mismatches with External APIs

**Description:** AI assumes API response shapes that don't match reality, or generates TypeScript interfaces that diverge from actual backend schemas.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  email: string;
  profile: { bio: string };
}

// Assumes shape without validation
const user: User = apiResponse;
console.log(user.profile.bio); // Crashes if profile is null or structure differs
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

const userSchema = z.object({
  id: z.number(),
  email: z.string(),
  profile: z.object({ bio: z.string() }).optional(),
});

type User = z.infer<typeof userSchema>;

const result = userSchema.safeParse(apiResponse);
if (result.success) {
  console.log(result.data.profile?.bio);
} else {
  console.error('Invalid API response:', result.error);
}
```

**Why AI does this:** AI generates plausible-looking interfaces from context but cannot verify them against the actual API. It "cannot make such strategic choices based on team size, deployment complexity, or operational needs."

**Impact:** "Most production outages from AI-generated code trace back to data model mismatches." Silent failures where data is coerced incorrectly.

**Detection:** Runtime validation (Zod, io-ts, ajv). Contract testing. Integration tests against real APIs.

**Sources:**
- [Debugging AI-Generated Code: 8 Failure Patterns](https://www.augmentcode.com/guides/debugging-ai-generated-code-8-failure-patterns-and-fixes)

