## 3. SECURITY VULNERABILITIES

### 3.1 SQL Injection via String Interpolation

**Description:** AI frequently uses template literals or string concatenation to build SQL queries with user input, creating injection vulnerabilities.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
const query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '${userEmail}'`;
db.query(query);

// Or with template literal
const query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ${userId}`;
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Parameterized query
const query = 'SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1';
db.query(query, [userEmail]);

// Or with an ORM
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
  where: { email: userEmail },
});
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data contains many examples of string interpolation. AI optimizes for readability and "making code work, not making code secure." A 2025 study found 45% of AI-generated code contains vulnerabilities.

**Impact:** Full database compromise. Data exfiltration. Authentication bypass.

**Detection:** CodeQL, Semgrep, ESLint `no-sql-injection` rules. SAST tools in CI/CD.

**Sources:**
- [Security Vulnerabilities in AI-Generated Code](https://www.endorlabs.com/learn/the-most-common-security-vulnerabilities-in-ai-generated-code)
- [OpenSSF Security Guide for AI Code Assistants](https://best.openssf.org/Security-Focused-Guide-for-AI-Code-Assistant-Instructions)

---

### 3.2 Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) via innerHTML

**Description:** AI uses `innerHTML` or `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with user-supplied content without sanitization.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// Vanilla JS/TS
element.innerHTML = userInput;

// React
function Comment({ text }: { text: string }) {
  return <div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: text }} />;
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Vanilla JS/TS
element.textContent = userInput;

// React - default behavior is safe
function Comment({ text }: { text: string }) {
  return <div>{text}</div>; // React auto-escapes
}

// If HTML is needed, sanitize first
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';
function Comment({ html }: { html: string }) {
  return <div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: DOMPurify.sanitize(html) }} />;
}
```

**Why AI does this:** AI may generate `innerHTML` when asked to render dynamic content. It doesn't reason about trust boundaries.

**Impact:** Stored/reflected XSS, session hijacking, credential theft.

**Detection:** ESLint `no-inner-html` rule. React ESLint plugin flags `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`. Content Security Policy headers.

**Sources:**
- [TypeScript XSS Guide](https://www.stackhawk.com/blog/typescript-xss-guide-examples-and-prevention/)
- [OpenSSF Security Guide](https://best.openssf.org/Security-Focused-Guide-for-AI-Code-Assistant-Instructions)

---

### 3.3 Command Injection

**Description:** AI uses `child_process.exec` with unsanitized user input to execute shell commands.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
import { exec } from 'child_process';

function convertFile(filename: string) {
  exec(`convert ${filename} output.png`); // Shell injection
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
import { execFile } from 'child_process';

function convertFile(filename: string) {
  execFile('convert', [filename, 'output.png']); // Array args, no shell
}
```

**Why AI does this:** `exec` with template strings is the simplest pattern. AI rarely considers adversarial inputs.

**Impact:** Remote code execution. Complete server compromise.

**Detection:** ESLint `security/detect-child-process` rule. SAST tools. Code review.

---

### 3.4 Hardcoded Secrets and Credentials

**Description:** AI embeds API keys, passwords, and tokens directly in source code.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
const API_KEY = 'sk-1234567890abcdef';
const client = new ApiClient({ apiKey: API_KEY });

// Or in config files
const dbConfig = {
  host: 'production-db.example.com',
  password: 'super_secret_password',
};
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function getApiClient(): ApiClient {
  const apiKey = process.env.API_KEY;
  if (!apiKey) {
    throw new Error('API_KEY environment variable is required');
  }
  return new ApiClient({ apiKey });
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Training examples often include placeholder credentials. AI fills in realistic-looking values.

**Impact:** Credential exposure in version control. Account takeover.

**Detection:** git-secrets, truffleHog, GitHub secret scanning, ESLint `no-hardcoded-credentials` rules.

**Sources:**
- [OpenSSF Security Guide](https://best.openssf.org/Security-Focused-Guide-for-AI-Code-Assistant-Instructions)
- [Security Vulnerabilities in AI-Generated Code](https://www.endorlabs.com/learn/the-most-common-security-vulnerabilities-in-ai-generated-code)

---

### 3.5 Prototype Pollution

**Description:** AI generates recursive merge functions or uses unsafe object spread patterns that are vulnerable to `__proto__` pollution.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
function deepMerge(target: any, source: any): any {
  for (const key in source) {
    if (typeof source[key] === 'object' && source[key] !== null) {
      target[key] = deepMerge(target[key] || {}, source[key]);
    } else {
      target[key] = source[key]; // __proto__ can be polluted
    }
  }
  return target;
}

// User input: { "__proto__": { "isAdmin": true } }
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function deepMerge<T extends Record<string, unknown>>(
  target: T,
  source: Partial<T>
): T {
  const result = { ...target };
  for (const key of Object.keys(source)) {
    if (key === '__proto__' || key === 'constructor' || key === 'prototype') {
      continue; // Skip dangerous keys
    }
    if (
      typeof source[key as keyof T] === 'object' &&
      source[key as keyof T] !== null &&
      !Array.isArray(source[key as keyof T])
    ) {
      result[key as keyof T] = deepMerge(
        result[key as keyof T] as any,
        source[key as keyof T] as any
      );
    } else {
      result[key as keyof T] = source[key as keyof T] as T[keyof T];
    }
  }
  return result;
}

// Or preferably: use a well-tested library like lodash.merge or structuredClone
```

**Why AI does this:** Recursive merge is a common pattern in training data, and most examples don't include prototype pollution guards.

**Impact:** Property injection on all objects, leading to authentication bypass, DoS, or RCE.

**Detection:** ESLint `security/detect-object-injection` rule. Snyk, npm audit. Use `Object.create(null)` for dictionaries.

**Sources:**
- [OWASP Prototype Pollution Prevention](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Prototype_Pollution_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)
- [Prototype Pollution in TypeScript](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/28596)

---

### 3.6 Missing Input Validation

**Description:** AI frequently omits input validation entirely unless explicitly prompted. Even when prompted, validation may be inconsistent or simplistic.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
app.post('/api/users', async (req, res) => {
  const { email, name, age } = req.body; // No validation
  await db.users.create({ email, name, age });
  res.json({ success: true });
});
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

const createUserSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email().max(255),
  name: z.string().min(1).max(100),
  age: z.number().int().min(0).max(150),
});

app.post('/api/users', async (req, res) => {
  const result = createUserSchema.safeParse(req.body);
  if (!result.success) {
    return res.status(400).json({ errors: result.error.flatten() });
  }
  await db.users.create(result.data);
  res.json({ success: true });
});
```

**Why AI does this:** "AI-generated code frequently omits input validation unless explicitly prompted to include it."

**Impact:** Injection attacks, data corruption, unexpected runtime errors.

**Detection:** SAST tools. API testing. Code review checklist for all external inputs.

---

## 4. PERFORMANCE ANTI-PATTERNS

### 4.1 O(n^2) Algorithms Where O(n) Suffices

**Description:** AI generates nested loops and string concatenation patterns that become performance bottlenecks at scale. GPT-4 generated code has been measured running 3x slower than human solutions.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// String concatenation in loop - O(n^2)
let result = '';
for (const item of largeArray) {
  result += item + ', ';
}

// Nested loop for lookup - O(n^2)
function findCommon(arr1: number[], arr2: number[]): number[] {
  return arr1.filter(item => arr2.includes(item));
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Array join - O(n)
const result = largeArray.join(', ');

// Set lookup - O(n)
function findCommon(arr1: number[], arr2: number[]): number[] {
  const set2 = new Set(arr2);
  return arr1.filter(item => set2.has(item));
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Development test datasets are too small to expose algorithmic complexity problems. The naive approach is the most common in training data.

**Impact:** Timeouts and degraded performance under production load. Memory pressure from unnecessary allocations.

**Detection:** Performance profiling (Clinic.js, Node.js profiler). Big-O analysis during code review. Benchmark tests.

**Sources:**
- [Debugging AI-Generated Code](https://www.augmentcode.com/guides/debugging-ai-generated-code-8-failure-patterns-and-fixes)
- [Common Bugs in AI-Generated Code](https://www.ranger.net/post/common-bugs-ai-generated-code-fixes)

---

### 4.2 Missing Event Listener Cleanup / Memory Leaks

**Description:** AI generates event listeners without corresponding cleanup, especially in React components, leading to memory leaks.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// React component
function SearchComponent() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');

  useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
    document.addEventListener('keydown', handleKeyPress);
    // No cleanup!
  }, []);

  // ...
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function SearchComponent() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleResize = () => { /* ... */ };
    const handleKeyPress = (e: KeyboardEvent) => { /* ... */ };

    window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
    document.addEventListener('keydown', handleKeyPress);

    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
      document.removeEventListener('keydown', handleKeyPress);
    };
  }, []);

  // ...
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Setup code is more prominent in training data than cleanup code. AI focuses on making features work, not on lifecycle management.

**Impact:** Memory leaks causing progressive performance degradation, crashes in long-running applications.

**Detection:** React `eslint-plugin-react-hooks`. Chrome DevTools memory profiling. `useEffect` dependency exhaustive-deps rule.

**Sources:**
- [Memory Leaks in React TypeScript](https://medium.com/@surenpoghosian/how-to-prevent-memory-leaks-in-react-typescript-b48d10edd8dc)

---

### 4.3 N+1 Query Problems

**Description:** AI generates code that makes individual database queries inside loops rather than batching.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
async function getUsersWithPosts(userIds: number[]) {
  const results = [];
  for (const id of userIds) {
    const user = await db.users.findOne({ id });
    const posts = await db.posts.find({ userId: id }); // N+1!
    results.push({ ...user, posts });
  }
  return results;
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
async function getUsersWithPosts(userIds: number[]) {
  const users = await db.users.findMany({
    where: { id: { in: userIds } },
    include: { posts: true },
  });
  return users;
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Iterative patterns are simpler to generate. AI doesn't reason about database round-trips.

**Impact:** Severe performance degradation. Each additional user adds a database round-trip.

**Detection:** ORM query logging. DataLoader pattern. Code review for `await` inside loops.

**Sources:**
- [AI-Assisted Development in 2026](https://dev.to/austinwdigital/ai-assisted-development-in-2026-best-practices-real-risks-and-the-new-bar-for-engineers-3fom)

---

### 4.4 Unnecessary Over-Abstraction

**Description:** AI creates excessive layers of abstraction -- wrapper functions, factory patterns, and abstract classes where simple direct code would suffice.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// AI generates enterprise-level abstraction for a simple task
interface ILoggerFactory {
  createLogger(name: string): ILogger;
}

interface ILogger {
  log(message: string): void;
}

class ConsoleLoggerFactory implements ILoggerFactory {
  createLogger(name: string): ILogger {
    return new ConsoleLogger(name);
  }
}

class ConsoleLogger implements ILogger {
  constructor(private name: string) {}
  log(message: string): void {
    console.log(`[${this.name}] ${message}`);
  }
}

// Usage
const factory = new ConsoleLoggerFactory();
const logger = factory.createLogger('app');
logger.log('Hello');
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function log(name: string, message: string): void {
  console.log(`[${name}] ${message}`);
}

log('app', 'Hello');
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data includes enterprise Java/C# patterns. AI applies them indiscriminately regardless of project scale.

**Impact:** Cognitive complexity. "Dozens of micro-abstractions without clear ownership." Harder to understand and maintain.

**Detection:** Cognitive complexity metrics. Code review. Cyclomatic complexity maximum of 10.

---

## 5. PACKAGE AND DEPENDENCY ISSUES

### 5.1 Hallucinated Packages (Slopsquatting)

**Description:** AI confidently recommends npm packages that do not exist. In ~20% of examined cases (across 576,000 samples), recommended packages didn't exist. Attackers can register these hallucinated package names with malicious code ("slopsquatting").

**Bad code:**
```typescript
import { validateEmail } from 'email-validator-pro'; // Doesn't exist
import { utilityFunction } from 'lodash-advanced'; // Doesn't exist
import { parse } from 'ts-migrate-parser'; // Hallucinated by ChatGPT
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
import validator from 'validator'; // Real, well-known package
import { merge } from 'lodash'; // Real, well-known package
import ts from 'typescript'; // Real, official package
```

**Why AI does this:** "A majority of hallucinations are not just random noise, but repeatable artifacts of how the models respond to certain prompts." Models generate plausible names based on naming conventions.

**Impact:** Supply chain attacks if an attacker registers the hallucinated package name. Build failures. Wasted developer time.

**Detection:** `npm install` will fail for non-existent packages. Verify all packages in npm registry before installation. Use lockfiles. ESLint `import/no-unresolved`.

**Sources:**
- [Slopsquatting: AI Hallucinations and Supply Chain Risk](https://fossa.com/blog/slopsquatting-ai-hallucinations-new-software-supply-chain-risk/)
- [AI Code Tools Widely Hallucinate Packages](https://www.darkreading.com/application-security/ai-code-tools-widely-hallucinate-packages)
- [AI-Hallucinated Code Dependencies](https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/ai-hallucinated-code-dependencies-become-new-supply-chain-risk/)
- [Package Hallucinations (Snyk)](https://snyk.io/articles/package-hallucinations/)

---

### 5.2 Outdated/Deprecated Library APIs

**Description:** AI training data contains deprecated packages and old API patterns. It recommends libraries that were archived years ago.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// 'request' was deprecated/archived in 2020
import * as request from 'request';
request.get(url, callback);

// Old Express error handling
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  res.status(500).send(err.message); // Leaks error details
});

// moment.js (legacy, 300KB+)
import moment from 'moment';
const date = moment().format('YYYY-MM-DD');
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Modern alternatives
const response = await fetch(url);

// Or with error handling
import { ofetch } from 'ofetch';
const data = await ofetch(url);

// date-fns (tree-shakeable, modern)
import { format } from 'date-fns';
const date = format(new Date(), 'yyyy-MM-dd');
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data cutoff and frequency bias. Older libraries appear more frequently in training data.

**Impact:** Known vulnerabilities (CVEs), missing security patches, larger bundle sizes, no maintenance.

**Detection:** `npm audit`. Check package last-published dates (should be recent). `npm outdated`. Dependency scanning in CI.

**Sources:**
- [Debugging AI-Generated Code](https://www.augmentcode.com/guides/debugging-ai-generated-code-8-failure-patterns-and-fixes)

---

### 5.3 Excessive Dependencies

**Description:** AI pulls in heavy dependencies for trivial tasks. A simple to-do list app generated by AI included 2-5 backend dependencies that weren't needed.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
import _ from 'lodash'; // 72KB for one function

const unique = _.uniq(array);
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
const unique = [...new Set(array)];
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data frequently imports popular libraries. AI doesn't evaluate whether a native alternative exists.

**Impact:** Larger bundle size, more attack surface, more maintenance burden, slower builds.

**Detection:** Bundle analysis (webpack-bundle-analyzer). Dependency review. `you-dont-need-lodash` patterns.

---

## 6. ERROR HANDLING PROBLEMS

### 6.1 Swallowed Errors (Empty Catch Blocks)

**Description:** AI wraps code in try/catch but does nothing meaningful with the error, silently hiding failures.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
async function fetchData(url: string) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url);
    return response.json();
  } catch (e) {
    console.log(e); // Swallowed - caller doesn't know it failed
  }
}

// Or worse:
try {
  await riskyOperation();
} catch (e) {
  // empty
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
async function fetchData(url: string): Promise<ApiResponse> {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url);
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new HttpError(response.status, `HTTP ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`);
    }
    return response.json();
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof HttpError) {
      throw error;
    }
    throw new NetworkError('Failed to fetch data', { cause: error });
  }
}
```

**Why AI does this:** AI adds try/catch because it's the expected pattern, but doesn't reason about error propagation or recovery strategies.

**Impact:** Silent failures in production. Difficult debugging. Data corruption from partial operations.

**Detection:** ESLint `no-empty` and `@typescript-eslint/no-empty-function`. Code review for catch blocks.

---

### 6.2 Information Leakage in Error Messages

**Description:** AI exposes internal system details, stack traces, and database schemas in error responses.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
app.use((err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
  res.status(500).json({
    error: err.message,
    stack: err.stack, // Exposes internal details!
    query: req.query, // Exposes user input
  });
});
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
app.use((err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
  const errorId = crypto.randomUUID();
  logger.error('Request failed', { errorId, error: err, path: req.path });

  res.status(500).json({
    error: 'Internal server error',
    errorId, // For support correlation
  });
});
```

**Why AI does this:** Training data includes development-mode error handlers. AI doesn't distinguish between dev and production contexts.

**Impact:** Information disclosure. Attackers learn about internal architecture, database schemas, file paths.

**Detection:** Security testing. Penetration testing. SAST rules for error exposure.

**Sources:**
- [OpenSSF Security Guide](https://best.openssf.org/Security-Focused-Guide-for-AI-Code-Assistant-Instructions)

---

### 6.3 Catching `unknown` as Typed Error

**Description:** In TypeScript strict mode, caught errors are `unknown`, but AI treats them as `Error` objects.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
try {
  await someOperation();
} catch (error) {
  console.log(error.message); // Error: 'error' is of type 'unknown'
  console.log(error.stack);
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
try {
  await someOperation();
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof Error) {
    console.error(error.message);
  } else {
    console.error('Unknown error:', String(error));
  }
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Many training examples predate TypeScript's `useUnknownInCatchVariables` (TS 4.4+). Older patterns treat `catch (error)` as implicitly typed `Error`.

**Impact:** TypeScript compile errors in strict mode. Runtime errors if a non-Error value is thrown.

**Detection:** TypeScript `useUnknownInCatchVariables: true` (included in `strict`).

---

## 7. ASYNC/AWAIT AND PROMISE MISTAKES

### 7.1 Floating Promises (Forgotten Await)

**Description:** AI calls async functions without `await`, creating floating promises whose rejections go unhandled.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
function saveAndNotify(user: User) {
  saveToDatabase(user); // Returns Promise, not awaited!
  sendNotification(user.email); // Returns Promise, not awaited!
  console.log('Done'); // Runs before save/notify complete
}

// In Express route
app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
  createUser(req.body); // Floating promise
  res.json({ success: true }); // Responds before user is created
});
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
async function saveAndNotify(user: User): Promise<void> {
  await saveToDatabase(user);
  await sendNotification(user.email);
  console.log('Done');
}

// In Express route
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    await createUser(req.body);
    res.json({ success: true });
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Failed to create user' });
  }
});
```

**Why AI does this:** AI sometimes generates function calls without recognizing they return promises. The pattern looks correct syntactically.

**Impact:** Race conditions. Unhandled promise rejections (crash in Node.js). Data inconsistency.

**Detection:** ESLint `@typescript-eslint/no-floating-promises` (critical rule). `@typescript-eslint/no-misused-promises`.

**Sources:**
- [no-floating-promises rule](https://typescript-eslint.io/rules/no-floating-promises/)
- [no-misused-promises rule](https://typescript-eslint.io/rules/no-misused-promises/)

---

### 7.2 Sequential Awaits Where Parallel Is Appropriate

**Description:** AI awaits promises sequentially when they could run in parallel, creating unnecessary latency.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
async function fetchDashboard(userId: string) {
  const user = await fetchUser(userId); // 200ms
  const posts = await fetchPosts(userId); // 300ms
  const notifications = await fetchNotifications(userId); // 150ms
  // Total: 650ms sequential
  return { user, posts, notifications };
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
async function fetchDashboard(userId: string) {
  const [user, posts, notifications] = await Promise.all([
    fetchUser(userId),
    fetchPosts(userId),
    fetchNotifications(userId),
  ]);
  // Total: ~300ms parallel
  return { user, posts, notifications };
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Sequential await is the simpler, more common pattern in training data. AI doesn't analyze data dependencies.

**Impact:** 2-5x slower response times for operations that could be parallelized.

**Detection:** Code review for consecutive independent `await` calls. Performance monitoring.

---

### 7.3 Promises Passed Where Callbacks or Booleans Are Expected

**Description:** AI passes async functions to APIs that expect synchronous callbacks, such as `Array.forEach`, or uses promises in boolean contexts.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// forEach doesn't await - all promises fire simultaneously with no error handling
users.forEach(async (user) => {
  await sendEmail(user.email);
});
console.log('All emails sent'); // Runs immediately, not after sends

// Promise in boolean context (always truthy)
if (fetchUser(id)) { // This is a Promise, always truthy!
  console.log('User exists');
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Use for...of for sequential
for (const user of users) {
  await sendEmail(user.email);
}

// Or Promise.all for parallel
await Promise.all(users.map(user => sendEmail(user.email)));

// Await the promise
const user = await fetchUser(id);
if (user) {
  console.log('User exists');
}
```

**Why AI does this:** `forEach` is extremely common in training data. AI doesn't distinguish between sync and async iteration contexts.

**Impact:** Silent failures. Race conditions. Logic errors from truthy promise objects.

**Detection:** ESLint `@typescript-eslint/no-misused-promises`. `no-return-await` rules.

---

### 7.4 Missing Error Handling in Promise Chains

**Description:** AI creates promise chains or `Promise.all` calls without handling rejections.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
async function fetchAllData(urls: string[]) {
  const results = await Promise.all(
    urls.map(url => fetch(url).then(r => r.json()))
  );
  // If ANY fetch fails, ALL results are lost
  return results;
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
async function fetchAllData(urls: string[]) {
  const results = await Promise.allSettled(
    urls.map(url => fetch(url).then(r => r.json()))
  );

  return results.map((result, i) => {
    if (result.status === 'fulfilled') {
      return { url: urls[i], data: result.value, error: null };
    }
    return { url: urls[i], data: null, error: result.reason };
  });
}
```

**Why AI does this:** `Promise.all` is the more common pattern. `Promise.allSettled` is newer and less represented in training data.

**Impact:** One failure causes total data loss from all parallel requests.

**Detection:** Code review for `Promise.all` with external calls. Consider `Promise.allSettled` for fault tolerance.

---

## 8. REACT / NEXT.JS SPECIFIC ISSUES

### 8.1 Unnecessary useEffect for Derived State

**Description:** AI uses `useState` + `useEffect` to compute values that could be calculated during render. This is one of the most common React anti-patterns AI produces.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
function ProductList({ products }: { products: Product[] }) {
  const [filteredProducts, setFilteredProducts] = useState<Product[]>([]);
  const [totalPrice, setTotalPrice] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    const filtered = products.filter(p => p.inStock);
    setFilteredProducts(filtered);
    setTotalPrice(filtered.reduce((sum, p) => sum + p.price, 0));
  }, [products]);

  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>;
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function ProductList({ products }: { products: Product[] }) {
  const filteredProducts = products.filter(p => p.inStock);
  const totalPrice = filteredProducts.reduce((sum, p) => sum + p.price, 0);

  // If expensive, use useMemo
  // const filteredProducts = useMemo(
  //   () => products.filter(p => p.inStock),
  //   [products]
  // );

  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>;
}
```

**Why AI does this:** "useState and useEffect are antipatterns" for synchronous derived data, but they're the most common hooks in training data. AI defaults to what it sees most often.

**Impact:** Unnecessary re-renders (renders once with stale data, then again with computed data). Flash of incorrect content. Performance degradation.

**Detection:** React DevTools profiler. ESLint `react-hooks/exhaustive-deps`. The official React docs: "You Might Not Need an Effect."

**Sources:**
- [You Might Not Need an Effect (React docs)](https://react.dev/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect)
- [Common React Anti-Patterns](https://oozou.com/blog/6-react-anti-patterns-to-avoid-206)
- [Why AI-Generated React and Next.js Code Breaks](https://medium.com/@prakashjhandls/why-ai-generated-react-and-next-js-code-breaks-and-how-i-fix-it-quickly-efc8c5fd587a)

---

### 8.2 Missing useEffect Cleanup

**Description:** AI adds subscriptions, timers, and event listeners in useEffect without returning a cleanup function.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  const interval = setInterval(pollApi, 5000);
  const ws = new WebSocket('ws://api.example.com');
  ws.onmessage = (event) => setData(JSON.parse(event.data));
  // No cleanup! Memory leak + stale updates
}, []);
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  const interval = setInterval(pollApi, 5000);
  const ws = new WebSocket('ws://api.example.com');
  ws.onmessage = (event) => setData(JSON.parse(event.data));

  return () => {
    clearInterval(interval);
    ws.close();
  };
}, []);
```

**Why AI does this:** Cleanup logic is less prominent in training data. AI focuses on the "setup" side of effects.

**Impact:** Memory leaks, stale state updates after unmount, "Can't perform a React state update on an unmounted component" warnings.

**Detection:** `eslint-plugin-react-hooks` exhaustive-deps rule. React StrictMode (double-invokes effects in development).

---

### 8.3 Incorrect useEffect Dependency Arrays

**Description:** AI either omits dependencies (causing stale closures) or includes too many (causing infinite re-render loops).

**Bad code (missing deps):**
```typescript
function SearchResults({ query }: { query: string }) {
  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchResults(query).then(setResults);
  }, []); // Missing 'query' dependency - stale closure!

  return <div>{results.map(/* ... */)}</div>;
}
```

**Bad code (infinite loop):**
```typescript
function UserProfile({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  const options = { include: 'posts' }; // New object every render

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchUser(userId, options).then(setUser);
  }, [userId, options]); // options changes every render = infinite loop
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
function SearchResults({ query }: { query: string }) {
  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false;
    fetchResults(query).then((data) => {
      if (!cancelled) setResults(data);
    });
    return () => { cancelled = true; };
  }, [query]);

  return <div>{results.map(/* ... */)}</div>;
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Dependency arrays require understanding the closure semantics of JavaScript, which AI models struggle with.

**Detection:** `react-hooks/exhaustive-deps` ESLint rule. React StrictMode.

---

### 8.4 Hallucinated Next.js Routes and APIs

**Description:** AI generates Next.js API routes, middleware, or page paths that don't exist in the project structure or don't match the framework version (Pages Router vs. App Router).

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// AI mixes App Router and Pages Router patterns
// In app/api/users/route.ts (App Router)
export default function handler(req, res) { // Pages Router pattern!
  res.status(200).json({ users: [] });
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// App Router pattern (app/api/users/route.ts)
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';

export async function GET() {
  return NextResponse.json({ users: [] });
}

// Pages Router pattern (pages/api/users.ts)
import type { NextApiRequest, NextApiResponse } from 'next';

export default function handler(req: NextApiRequest, res: NextApiResponse) {
  res.status(200).json({ users: [] });
}
```

**Why AI does this:** Next.js has had multiple major routing paradigms. Training data contains both, and AI conflates them.

**Impact:** Broken routes, 404 errors, incorrect request handling.

**Detection:** Next.js build errors. Integration tests. Verify route file locations match the router pattern.

**Sources:**
- [Why AI-Generated React and Next.js Code Breaks](https://medium.com/@prakashjhandls/why-ai-generated-react-and-next-js-code-breaks-and-how-i-fix-it-quickly-efc8c5fd587a)

---

### 8.5 Client/Server Boundary Confusion

**Description:** AI uses browser APIs in server components or server-only APIs in client components.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// app/components/UserList.tsx (Server Component by default in App Router)
export default function UserList() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]); // useState in server component!
  // ...
}
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// app/components/UserList.tsx (Server Component)
export default async function UserList() {
  const users = await db.users.findMany();
  return <ul>{users.map(u => <li key={u.id}>{u.name}</li>)}</ul>;
}

// app/components/UserSearch.tsx (Client Component)
'use client';
import { useState } from 'react';

export default function UserSearch() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
  // ...
}
```

**Why AI does this:** The App Router server/client boundary is relatively new. Training data heavily favors the older client-side-only React patterns.

**Impact:** Build errors. Hydration mismatches. Leaked secrets in client bundles if server code runs on client.

