## 9. TESTING ANTI-PATTERNS

### 9.1 Over-Mocking (Testing Nothing Real)

**Description:** AI mocks every dependency so heavily that tests only verify mocked behavior, not actual application logic. Coverage appears high while catching zero real bugs.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// Tests mock everything - tests nothing real
jest.mock('./database');
jest.mock('./emailService');
jest.mock('./logger');
jest.mock('./validator');

test('createUser creates a user', async () => {
  (database.save as jest.Mock).mockResolvedValue({ id: 1 });
  (validator.validate as jest.Mock).mockReturnValue(true);

  const result = await createUser({ name: 'Test' });

  expect(database.save).toHaveBeenCalled(); // Only verifies the mock was called
  expect(result).toEqual({ id: 1 }); // Only verifies mock return value
});
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Integration test with real (test) database
test('createUser creates a user with valid data', async () => {
  const user = await createUser({
    name: 'Test User',
    email: 'test@example.com',
  });

  expect(user.id).toBeDefined();
  expect(user.name).toBe('Test User');

  // Verify in database
  const saved = await db.users.findUnique({ where: { id: user.id } });
  expect(saved).not.toBeNull();
  expect(saved?.email).toBe('test@example.com');
});

test('createUser rejects invalid email', async () => {
  await expect(
    createUser({ name: 'Test', email: 'not-an-email' })
  ).rejects.toThrow('Invalid email');
});
```

**Why AI does this:** "AI agents mock so heavily they test nothing real." AI produces surface-level correctness. Mocking is the most common pattern in training data for test files.

**Impact:** "A test suite with 100% coverage but 4% mutation score executes every line and misses 96% of potential bugs."

**Detection:** Mutation testing (Stryker). Review mock count per test. Integration tests should outnumber unit tests for service logic.

**Sources:**
- [How to Test AI-Generated Code the Right Way](https://www.twocents.software/blog/how-to-test-ai-generated-code-the-right-way/)
- [AI vs Human Code Generation Report](https://www.coderabbit.ai/blog/state-of-ai-vs-human-code-generation-report)

---

### 9.2 Tests That Test AI's Assumptions, Not Requirements

**Description:** AI generates tests that validate its own implementation rather than the actual business requirements.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
// AI tests its own implementation detail
test('formatPrice returns formatted price', () => {
  expect(formatPrice(10)).toBe('$10.00'); // What if locale is EUR?
});

test('getDiscount calculates discount', () => {
  expect(getDiscount(100, 10)).toBe(90); // Does this match the business rule?
  // Missing: volume discounts, membership tiers, minimum order, etc.
});
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
// Tests based on business requirements
describe('formatPrice', () => {
  test('formats USD price with 2 decimal places', () => {
    expect(formatPrice(10, 'USD')).toBe('$10.00');
  });

  test('formats EUR price with European convention', () => {
    expect(formatPrice(10, 'EUR')).toBe('10,00 EUR');
  });

  test('handles zero price', () => {
    expect(formatPrice(0, 'USD')).toBe('$0.00');
  });

  test('rounds to nearest cent', () => {
    expect(formatPrice(10.999, 'USD')).toBe('$11.00');
  });
});
```

**Why AI does this:** AI "tests its own assumptions rather than actual intent" and "rarely includes complex edge cases, domain-specific constraints, or legacy system integration needs."

**Impact:** False confidence. Tests pass but don't catch regressions in business logic.

**Detection:** Review tests against requirements docs. Mutation testing. Coverage of edge cases.

---

### 9.3 Snapshot Test Overuse

**Description:** AI generates snapshot tests for components that change frequently, leading to meaningless snapshot updates that are rubber-stamped.

**Bad code:**
```typescript
test('renders UserDashboard', () => {
  const { container } = render(<UserDashboard user={mockUser} />);
  expect(container).toMatchSnapshot(); // 500-line snapshot that changes with every UI tweak
});
```

**Good code:**
```typescript
test('displays user name and email', () => {
  render(<UserDashboard user={mockUser} />);
  expect(screen.getByText('John Doe')).toBeInTheDocument();
  expect(screen.getByText('john@example.com')).toBeInTheDocument();
});

test('shows edit button for authenticated users', () => {
  render(<UserDashboard user={mockUser} isAuthenticated />);
  expect(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /edit profile/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

**Why AI does this:** Snapshot tests are the simplest way to "test" a component. AI optimizes for ease of generation.

**Impact:** Snapshot fatigue. Developers blindly update snapshots without reviewing changes.

**Detection:** Limit snapshot size. Prefer targeted assertions with Testing Library. Code review for snapshot tests.

